         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">7/6/82. ¶  ¶ The name Galeola was derived by Loureiro from Galea, a leather-helmet, dear Mr Fitzgerald, in allusion to the shape of the labellum. ¶  ¶ Dendrobium Smillieae was dedicated to Mrs E. J. S...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">82.06.07</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To Robert Fitzgerald</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">MS 826, Fitzgerald papers, National Library of Australia, Canberra.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">7/6/82.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The name Galeola was derived by Loureiro from Galea, a leather-helmet, dear Mr Fitzgerald, in allusion to the shape of the labellum.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <name key="Dendrobium%20Smillieae">Dendrobium Smillieae</name> was dedicated to Mrs E. J. Smillie, the widow of the honorable Mr Smillie, the first Advocate General of the Colony of South Australia.<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>B67.12.01, p. 94.</p>
               </note> The Lady has a particular taste for floral beauties, and as a friend of the family since the earlier part of South Australian colonisation, I named this plant to cheer up the drooping spirit, when through the successive death of two accomplished children the Lady was thrown into the deepest of sadness.<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>William Matthews Smillie, only son of William Smillie and his wife Eliza Jane née Farquharson, died at Aberdeen on 23 October 1867, aged 17 (<seg style="font-style: italic; ">Argus</seg>, 18 December 1867, p. 4); his sister Elizabeth Smillie, the youngest daughter of the family, died at St Leonard's-on-the-Sea, England, on 4 September 1869, aged 21 (<seg style="font-style: italic; ">Argus</seg>, 27 October 1869, p. 4). M named the species in B67.12.01, possibly in response to news of the son's death, but the daughter was still alive at this time.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The authority of all the Austral. plant-genera is given in the volume of the R.S.<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Royal Society.</p>
               </note> of N.S.W. of 1881,<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>See B82.07.05.</p>
               </note> which will likely very soon appear, but I had then not established yet the genus <name key="Fitzgeraldia">Fitzgeraldia</name> (the homonymous genus among <name key="Anonaceae">Anonaceae</name> I have found previously to be identical with the Indian genus <name key="Cananga">Cananga</name>).</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>G. Reichenbach stands sponsor to G. cassythoides.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <name key="Diuris">Diuris</name> Smith in the transact. of the L.S.<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Linnean Society, London.</p>
               </note> IV, 222 (1798)</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>B<seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">u</hi>
               </seg>lbophyllum, Du Petit-Thouars Histoire des plantes Orchidées recueillies sur les trois îles australes d'Afrique (de France, de Bourbon et de Madagascar) t. 95 &amp; 108 (1822)<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Du Petit-Thouars (1822).</p>
               </note> Sprengel changed without cause the name later into B<seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">o</hi>
               </seg>lbophyllum.<note xml:id="ftn7" type="footnote" n="7">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Sprengel (1825-8), vol. 3, p. 681.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <name key="Cleisostoma">Cleisostoma</name>, Blume Bijdragen tot de Flora van Nederlandsch Indie 362 (1825)</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Dendrobium, Swartz in nov. act. Upsaliens. VI, 82 (1799)</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <name key="Spathoglottis">Spathoglottis</name>, Blume Bijdragen 400 (1825)</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <name key="Spiranthes">Spiranthes</name>, L.C. Richard in Memoires du Muséum, Paris, IV, 40 (1818)</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <name key="Lyperanthes">Lyperanthes</name>,<note xml:id="ftn8" type="footnote" n="8">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Lyperanthus?</p>
               </note> R. Brown prodromus florae Novae Hollandiae 325 (1810).</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <name key="Dendrobium%20Smillieae">Dendrobium Smillieae</name> is limited to N E. Queensland, where in a few places it occurs in the jungle forests</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <name key="Cleisostoma">Cleisostoma</name> is recently reduced by Bentham to <name key="Sarcochilus">Sarcochilus</name>, as suggested by me 20 years ago.<note xml:id="ftn9" type="footnote" n="9">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Bentham maintained both genera in Bentham &amp; Hooker (1862-83), vol. 3, part 2, p. 478, issued in April 1883 (TL2); Bentham (1881), pp. 333-55 contains a discussion of these and related genera, without however making an explicit general reduction. </p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I was greatly pleased to see your many new Orchids of W.A. appear in the Gardeners Chronicle.<note xml:id="ftn10" type="footnote" n="10">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>R. Fitzgerald (1882).</p>
               </note>
               <name key="Thelymitra%20rubra">Thelymitra rubra</name> of W.A. requires comparison with T. MacKibbinii, described last year from Victoria.<note xml:id="ftn11" type="footnote" n="11">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>B81.10.01, p. 44.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Very regardfully your</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd. von Mueller</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">I am greatly pleased to hear, that your new part of the superb Orchid work<note xml:id="ftn12" type="footnote" n="12">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>R. Fitzgerald (1875-94), vol 1, part 7, did not appear until October 1882; see review in <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Sydney morning herald</seg>, 1 November 1882, p. 5.</p>
               </note> will very soon appear. I like to <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">purchase</hi>
               </seg> one copy of the new part for Mrs Smillie, now in Florence.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I have not yet made up my mind concerning the fern from Howe's Island,<note xml:id="ftn13" type="footnote" n="13">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>i.e. Lord Howe Island.</p>
               </note> kindly sent by you.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I had no idea, that Thelym. McKibbinii might extend to W.A.</p>
